  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Reducing ERW Casualties Amongst Conflict-Displaced and Vulnerable People in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Under this project, HALO plans to deploy seven mobile cross-trained Survey/Explosive Ordnance Disposal (EOD) teams across eastern and southern Afghanistan in support of HRP SO2. HALO will deploy four cross-trained Survey/EOD teams in the south, covering Helmand, Kandarhar, and Nimroz provinces, and three teams in the east, covering Nangarhar, Kunar, and Laghman provinces. HALO will prioritise visiting communities that are hosting large numbers of conflict-displaced people and communities which have been affected by recent fighting where displaced people are returning after fighting dies down. Community survey will be particularly important as the 2016 summer fighting season subsides and people begin to return to their homes, many of which will be contaminated and require clearance. HALO&#x2019;s cross-trained teams will conduct three related activities to improve physical security and provide protection from the threat of ERW. 

Firstly, the teams will provide Mine Risk Education (MRE) to conflict-displaced people who are living in displacement and to people who are living in communities recently affected by heavy fighting. Secondly, the teams will locate communities that have been left contaminated with ERW by recent conflict to do this, they will conduct a village-by-village survey process in districts where heavy fighting has taken place, recording communities as impacted by ERW or non-impacted. In the course of this work, they will conduct a third activity: spot Explosive Ordnance Disposal (EOD) of any dangerous items they come across during village surveys or that are reported to them during MRE sessions. If large-scale ERW contamination is identified, HALO will deploy WAD and CWD teams funded by other donors to clear the contaminated areas at no cost to this project.</narrative>
  </description>
